[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] In computer programming, the word **trampoline** has a number of meanings, and is generally associated with jump instructions (i.e. moving to different code paths).
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] Trampolines (sometimes referred to as indirect jump vectors) are memory locations holding addresses pointing to interrupt service routines, I/O routines, etc.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] Execution jumps into the trampoline and then immediately jumps out, or bounces, hence the term *trampoline*.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] Some implementations of trampolines cause a loss of no-execute stacks (NX stack).
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] In the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) in particular, a nested function builds a trampoline on the stack at runtime, and then calls the nested function through the data on stack.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] The trampoline requires the stack to be executable.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] No-execute stacks and nested functions are mutually exclusive under GCC.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] If a nested function is used in the development of a program, then the NX stack is silently lost.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] GCC offers the `-Wtrampolines` warning to alert of the condition.
[src:continuation-passing-style/trampoline-computing] Software engineered using secure development lifecycle often do not allow the use of nested functions due to the loss of NX stacks.
